Effective data preprocessing is essential for ensuring model reliability and performance. The following steps were applied to prepare the dataset for DNI prediction:
Lagged feature generation. To capture temporal dependencies, we created lagged versions of every variable at 30-minute intervals up to 360 minutes (i.e., 30, 60, 90, …, 360). These features allow the model to leverage past observations when forecasting current DNI.
Missing value handling. Missing data were first identified and assessed for gap size. Small gaps were filled via linear interpolation, while larger gaps were imputed using mean or median values based on each variable’s distribution. Variables with excessive missingness that could compromise model integrity were excluded.
Normalization. All continuous variables were scaled to the range [0, 1] using min–max normalization. This step prevents features with larger magnitudes (e.g., temperature in \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^\circ$$\end{document}C vs. DNI in W/m2) from dominating the learning process.
Outlier detection and treatment. Values beyond 1.5 times the interquartile range (IQR) were flagged as outliers. Depending on their impact, outliers were either capped at the IQR thresholds or removed from the dataset.
Chronological data splitting. To avoid information leakage, the preprocessed data were split in time order into Training, Validation, and Test sets. The Training set was used for model fitting, the Validation set for hyperparameter tuning, and the Test set for final, unbiased performance evaluation.
Temporal consistency. Throughout preprocessing and splitting, the original chronological order was preserved to ensure that future observations never influenced earlier predictions.These preprocessing steps produced a clean, normalized, and temporally consistent dataset, providing a solid foundation for developing robust machine-learning models for DNI forecasting.

